l and immaterial infrastructures in imagining diverse urban futures: Dublin’s Bolt Hostel and Apollo House -- tConclusion: Centring vacancy – towards a research agenda -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book provides an innovative perspective to consider contemporary urban challenges through the lens of urban vacancy. Centering urban vacancy as a core feature of urbanization, the contributors coalesce new empirical insights on the impacts of recent contestations over the re-use of vacant spaces in post-crisis cities across the globe. Using international case studies from the Global North and Global South, it sheds important new light on the complexity of forces and processes shaping urban vacancy and its re-use, exploring these areas as both lived spaces and sites of political antagonism. It explores what has and hasn’t worked in re-purposing vacant sites and provides sustainable blueprints for future development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh1 aCaramaschi, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaulkins, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoppola, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Feliciantonio, Cesare, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeliciantonio, Cesare Di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreri, Mara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGribat, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJasper, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoscielniak, Michael R.J